      "known_gaps": ["M1 now exports schema-backed typed cap commit and RTL post-state projection records, checks the schema against Lean CommitOp/CommitStatus/CommitRecord/TypedCommitTransition/RtlM1StateProjection, requires Lean RTL commit/state projection structures and refinement-shape theorem names, emits post-state records from a typed_state_projection RTL module boundary, feeds that packed projection into local RTL assertions for transfer continuity, projection faithfulness against real RTL authority state, op/status agreement, non-OK authority-projection preservation, authority-write mediation, and transfer/mint validity mediation, and runs executable pre/commit/post refinement comparison. The Lean model names rtlM1CommitPackedSchema and rtlM1StateProjectionPackedSchema with width, layout-bounds, and contiguous-coverage theorems, defines schema-width-bounded packed-bit extraction for M1 commit/pre/post records, rejects unmodeled high rights bits in those packed witnesses, decodes M1 op/status enum values and authority rights masks into Lean projections, and proves that a packed pre/commit/post witness refines the Lean RTL refinement step, preserves SG-AUTH under the same pre-state invariant assumption, and keeps accepted status matched to the operation. The checker compares those Lean packed-schema mirrors plus the RTL lnp64_m1_cap_commit_t and lnp64_m1_state_projection_t packed typedef field order/widths to the shared RTL schema, consumes schema-owned M1 op/status mappings when checking SV enum names, Lean constructors, op/status agreement, and trace values, and now rejects drift in the Lean packed-bit decoders, missing packed-bit schema-width bounds, missing modeled-rights obligations, or missing packed-refinement theorem surface. The checker also requires every emitted M1 state projection trace field to be sourced from typed_state_projection, requires packed RTL commit/projection bit records to carry the schema width and decodes them by schema, checks each adjacent pre-state projection, typed commit projection, and post-state projection against the executable mirror of Lean RtlM1RefinementStep, and can emit a top-level JSON witness artifact containing checked commit/pre/post packed bits plus schema field order, widths, and a canonical record hash. The Lean refinement relation now lifts failed-authority and non-OK commit preservation onto RTL state projections, proves accepted commit status follows the commit op at both typed-transition and RTL-refinement levels, and has op-specific projection lemmas for capDup, capSend, capRecv, objectCreate, and capRevoke authority projections plus push/pull wake postconditions and rejectFull/rejectStale/capDupDenied failure postconditions. This is a stronger explicit refinement-shape bridge. The packed-bit codec and the M1 refinement step now live in one shared executable mirror (formal/m1_top_refinement.py) used by both the producer smoke and the offline witness consumer (scripts/check_rtl_top_m1_witness.py), which re-validates the generated top-level witness JSON against that mirror without the simulator (schema field order/widths, canonical records hash, packed-bit faithfulness, and the refinement step per record). scripts/run_rtl_m1_lean_witness_gate.sh (generator scripts/gen_m1_witness_lean.py) now proves in Lean, with the kernel decide tactic and no axioms, that every emitted commit/pre/post packed bit vector decodes under the Lnp64.M1Transition packed-bit decoders to exactly the recorded field/op/status values -- the first emitted-bits-to-Lean artifact. The remaining gap is the existential RtlM1RefinementStep and modeled-rights predicates per emitted record, still established generically in Lean and per-record only by the executable/Python mirror; no formal RTL-to-Lean bit-refinement proof that every emitted RTL bit vector satisfies the full Lean packed-bit refinement step exists yet."]
